node.text:
“You will be challenged during the next four years, but you can do it,” said Academy Superintendent Lt. Gen. Richard Clark. “Take one bite at a time. The first step is completing basic cadet training, and you have already demonstrated you have what it takes to succeed by getting here. I stood where you stand almost 40 years ago and I’m so glad I stuck it out.”

The global COVID-19 pandemic may be on the decline, but the Air Force Academy took no chances when more than 1,100 young men and women reported to the school for basic cadet training, June 24.

The trainees arrived between 7 a.m.-noon, were given facemasks, and immediately tested for the coronavirus.

Check out more on this story at www.usafa.edu.

node.text: Today, cadets march in a Founders Day Parade honoring the legacy of #youracademy. Together, we stand on the foundation built by those who came before us, striving to strengthen that foundation for those who come after us, reinforcing our bonds with a culture of dignity and respect. Being part of the Long Blue Line means being part of something bigger than ourselves, collectively building and bolstering the bridge to the future @usairforce  and  @spaceforcedod. The more we treat each other with dignity and respect, and ensure that this is a fundamental part of our culture, the higher we’ll rise together.

node.text:
As we honor Black History Month, I’d like to take a moment to share with you one of my favorite stories about Rosa Parks. I share this in hopes that when we think of civil rights exemplars such as Rosa Parks, the Tuskegee Airmen, Dr. Martin Luther King, and the many other pioneers of integration and racial equality, that we also reflect on ourselves. How can we better ourselves and understand that together we have an opportunity to become not only better Air and Space Forces, but a nation that champions diversity and inclusion?

node.text: Running with purpose. Colorado Spring ultrarunner Tim Gore recently joined the @af_tfxc cross country team for a warm-up run.  Gore is preparing for an ultra next weekend- that's running 150 miles... in one stretch!  And the Army veteran is hoping to bring attention to Suicide Prevention Awareness month.  He shared with the cadets not only his passion for running but for addressing veteran suicide because he says it's important for all service members and veterans to understand it's ok to ask for help.

Not only do these young men and women feel strongly about the events of that day- they are equally passionate about their commitment to serve their country and ensure #WeRemember911 for generations to come. node.text: Tomorrow is the 20th anniversary of 9/11.  It is also C2C Kai Gill's birthday.  Kai turned one year old on 9/11/01.  He didn't know it then, but his birthday would never really be the same.  He says his decision to serve in the United States Air Force came from the seed of service that was planted 20 years ago when firefighters sacrificed their lives so that others may live.  He says his birthday will always serve as a memorial and remind him of why he decided to serve his country and inspire future generations.  #WeRemember

node.text:
Emma Redmond, Class of 2024, doesn't remember 9/11, but growing up in New York, its impact was all around her as a child.  And as she grew older, her dad, a NY police officer, recently started sharing stories from that day. Her father just completed his 29th year with the force and Emma is dedicated to carrying on the family's commitment to service, here at the academy and beyond in the @usairforce. 
She is one of many cadets, who are part of the next generation, ready to ensure the country remembers 9/11 on this 20th anniversary and beyond. 
 #WeRemember911

Vice Superintendent of #youracademy, Col Otis Jones escorted Ms Kiki Homer during the US Open's Military Appreciation Day.

We continue our 9/11 cadet stories on the horizon of the 20th anniversary with the story of Carlos Arreola, Class of 2023. 

Carlos was with his grandmother that morning in 2001 and was confused by her reaction to what she was watching on tv.  Later, Carlos enlisted in the @usairforce and during a deployment to Afghanistan personally connected the 9/11 attacks to his life and his service, inspiring him to reach higher and be his best self for those who no longer could. 
#WeRemember911

As we approach the 20th anniversary of 9/11 we asked cadets- many of whom were not alive or old enough to remember the events of that day- how 9/11 has impacted their lives and their decision to serve. What we found is a passion to serve and dedication to not let America forget what happened in New York, at the Pentagon and in the skies above Pennsylvania 20 years ago. 

We start with the story of Max Buck, Class of 2024.  Max wasn't alive on 9/11, but the events that day hit hard and close to home.  Max's dad serves in the New York Fire Department - he was there on 9/11 and spent countless hours at Ground Zero in the weeks that followed. Max is at #youracademy today to serve his country, like his dad and those around him who served their country on the front lines in New York on 9/11. #WeRemember911
